flowRoot.flowPara: 1869 - first observation of cathode rays (later identified as electrons) in electric discharge through vacuum tubes by Johann Wilhelm Hittorf
1886 - discovery of anode rays (ions) by Eugen Goldstein
1898 - J. J. Thomson measures the m/z ratio of cathode rays (electrons)
1898 - demonstration by Wilhelm Wein that anode rays have much larger m/z than cathode rays
1901 - deflection by a magnetic field used to show that particles gain mass as their energy increases (relativistic mass).
1913 - 20Ne and 22Ne seperated by J. J. Thomson and his student Francis Aston. Isotopes are discovered!
1918 - electron ionization described by Author Dempster

1919 - Francis Aston finishes the first full mass spectrometer. Ionization is done in a discharge tube, mass selection by crossed electric and magnetic fields, and detection by luminescence in a discharge tube.
1931 - cyclotron invented by Ernest O. Lawrence. Ions are accelerated in a spiral by a constant magnetic field and radio-frequency alternating electric fields.
1941 - a mass spectrometer based on the cyclotron, called the calutron, is used to separate isotopes of uranium for the Manhattan Project.
1943 - first successful commercialization of a mass spectrometer by the Consolidated Engineering Corporation
1946 - first time-of-flight mass analyzer developed by W. Stephens
1953 - first quadrupole mass spectrometer by Wolfgang Paul and Helmut Steinwedel
1956 - first GC-MS by Roland Gohlke and Fred McLafferty
1962 - first QMS sold to NASA for residual gas analysis
1963 - MIMS invented by Hoch and Kok for study with MS of volatiles in liquids [A]
1966 - first use of mass spectrometry for peptide sequencing by Biemann, Cone, Webster, and Arsenault
1968 - electrospray ionization invented by Dole
1971 - first measurements of electrochemical products by Bruckenstein and Gadde [B]
1980 - inductively coupled plasma (ICP) first used as an ion source for mass spectrometry by Robert Houk et al.
1983 - matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI) developed by Tanaka, Karas, and Hillenkamp.
1984 - differential electrochemical mass spectrometry (DEMS) invented by Wolter and Heitbaum. [C]
2006 - online electrochemical mass spectrometry (OLEMS) developed by Marc Koper and coworkers. [D]
2009 - microreactor described by Henriksen et al for mass spectrometric analysis of the activity of a small amount of catalyst. [E]
2015 - electrochemical microreactor described by Trimarco et al. [F]
2018 - membrane chip and EC-MS described by Trimarco and Scott et al. [G]
